  "title": "Software for an Audience of One",
  "description": "Part 5 of a 6-part series on AI-native computing. The marginal cost of bespoke software collapsed to near zero, inverting the economics that forced fifty years of mass software. Code becomes disposable; intent and data are the assets. Companion video to the essay of the same name.",
  "lang": "en",
  "beats": [
    {
      "text": "Software for an audience of one. This is part five of a six part series about AI-native computing — the computer that understands, and the computer that builds. This part is about money. About what happens when building software stops being expensive.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "title",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "Part 5 of 6 · Beyond the Sea of App Icons"
          },
          "titleSize": "hero",
          "subtitleSize": "lead",
          "title": "Software for an **Audience of One**",
          "subtitle": "What happens when building software becomes {primary:nearly free}",
          "author": "Satoshi Nakajima",
          "chips": [
            "🗣️ the computer that understands",
            "🛠️ the computer that builds"
          ]
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Here is a real thing. A restaurant guide, drawn as a Tokyo subway map. The lines are neighborhoods. The stations are restaurants. It glows on one person's home screen, and it was made for exactly one person — its owner.",
