    {
      "text": "That map exists today. So does a flashcard drill for one person's vocabulary. And a poster wall for one person's watchlist. Each one is a small piece of software an agent wrote on request. The owner never saw a line of the code. He described what he wanted — and the software appeared.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "grid",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The claim"
          },
          "title": "Software with an audience of exactly one",
          "gridColumns": 3,
          "items": [
            {
              "title": "Subway map",
              "description": "one person's restaurants, as transit lines",
              "accentColor": "primary",
              "icon": "🚇"
            },
            {
              "title": "Flashcards",
              "description": "a drill for one person's vocabulary",
              "accentColor": "accent",
              "icon": "🎴"
            },
            {
              "title": "Poster wall",
              "description": "one person's movie watchlist",
              "accentColor": "info",
              "icon": "🎬"
            }
          ],
          "footer": "Three of six views in one real workspace. The owner never saw a line of the code."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "No company would ever build any of these. Maggie Appleton gave the category its exact name: software no industrial software company would build, because there is not enough market value in it. The market for that subway map is one person. For fifty years, that made it impossible. Not hard — impossible.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "bigQuote",
          "accentColor": "accent",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The category"
          },
          "quote": "“Software that no industrial software company would build — there's not enough market value in doing it.”",
          "author": "Maggie Appleton · Local-First conference, 2024",
          "role": "The addressable market is exactly one person"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Why impossible? Arithmetic. Building software was expensive — teams, years, paid up front. But serving one more user cost nothing. So the rational move was to spread that big fixed cost over as many users as possible. Build for the mass. And everyone gets the average.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "columns",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The old arithmetic",
            "color": "warning"
          },
          "title": "Why software was built for the mass",
          "columns": [
            {
              "title": "Building is expensive",
              "accentColor": "danger",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "**Teams. Years. Paid up front.**"
                }
              ],
              "num": 1
            },
            {
              "title": "One more user is free",
              "accentColor": "info",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "**Copying costs nothing.**"
                }
              ],
              "num": 2
            },
            {
              "title": "So: build for the mass",
              "accentColor": "warning",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "**Everyone gets the average.**"
                }
              ],
              "num": 3
            }
          ],
          "showArrows": true,
          "callout": {
            "text": "The workflow that's 80% right and forever 20% wrong — not bad taste, just {warning:the arithmetic.}",
            "label": "The symptom",
            "color": "warning",
            "leftBar": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Now remove one term. A model that writes working code on demand makes building nearly free. And the whole structure falls. If building for one person costs the same as building for millions, the reason to build for millions disappears. You build for exactly this person.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "comparison",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The collapse"
          },
          "title": "One term removed — the structure falls",
          "left": {
            "title": "Old arithmetic",
            "accentColor": "danger",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "metric",
                "value": "millions",
                "label": "of users to repay a build",
                "color": "danger"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "value": "Building is expensive → aim at the mass.",
                "size": "sub",
                "dim": true
              }
            ]
          },
          "right": {
            "title": "New arithmetic",
            "accentColor": "success",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "metric",
                "value": "1",
                "label": "user is a viable audience",
                "color": "success"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "value": "Building is nearly free → aim at this person.",
                "size": "sub",
                "dim": true
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "So a fifty-year-old rule flips. The code is disposable. Intent and data are the asset.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "bigQuote",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The one line to remember"
          },
          "quote": "The code is {warning:disposable}; intent and data are {primary:the asset.}",
          "author": "Software for an Audience of One",
          "role": "Part 5 of 6"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at where the value actually sits. The intent is durable — draw my restaurants as a subway map. The data is durable — the restaurants themselves. The code in between is just a middle step, regrown on demand. Also color the stations by cuisine? That opens no code review. It reissues the request.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "columns",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "Code as an intermediate representation"
          },
          "title": "The durable things are the two ends",
          "columns": [
            {
              "title": "Intent",
              "accentColor": "primary",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "tag",
                  "text": "DURABLE",
                  "color": "success"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "*“Draw my restaurants as a subway map.”*"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "title": "Code",
              "accentColor": "warning",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "tag",
                  "text": "DISPOSABLE",
                  "color": "danger"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Regrown on demand — never repaired."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "title": "Data",
              "accentColor": "success",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "tag",
                  "text": "DURABLE",
                  "color": "success"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "The restaurants themselves."
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "showArrows": true,
          "callout": {
            "text": "“Also color the stations by cuisine” opens no code review — it {primary:reissues the request.}",
            "label": "Maintenance",
            "color": "info",
            "leftBar": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "So nobody maintains this software. When it stops fitting, you say the sentence again — and a new version simply replaces the old one. It is cheaper to regrow the artifact than to repair it.",
      "image": {
        "type": "html_tailwind",
        "html": "<div class=\"w-[1280px] h-[720px] overflow-hidden relative flex flex-col\" style=\"background: radial-gradient(1200px 700px at 12% -10%, rgba(56,189,248,.16), transparent 60%), radial-gradient(1000px 600px at 100% 0%, rgba(129,140,248,.16), transparent 55%), linear-gradient(160deg,#0A0F24,#111A3A 55%,#16224D); color:#EEF2FF; font-family:Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif\">\n<div class=\"px-14 pt-9 text-center\">\n<div class=\"text-[13px] font-semibold uppercase\" style=\"color:#818CF8; letter-spacing:0.25em\">Maintenance</div>\n<div class=\"mt-2 text-[32px] font-bold\" style=\"font-family:Georgia,serif\">Cheaper to regrow than to repair</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flex-1 flex items-center gap-6 px-14\">\n<div class=\"relative rounded-2xl border p-5\" style=\"width:400px; height:340px; background:rgba(17,26,58,.5); border-color:rgba(159,176,216,.2)\">\n<div class=\"text-[15px] font-semibold mb-1\" style=\"color:#9FB0D8\">v1</div>\n<div style=\"height:270px\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 460 310\" class=\"w-full h-full\" opacity=\"0.55\">\n<path d=\"M30 170 H430\" stroke=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke-width=\"7\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/>\n<path d=\"M60 280 L400 60\" stroke=\"#5C6786\" stroke-width=\"7\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/>\n<path d=\"M60 80 L260 65 Q300 62 322 92 L390 180\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#79829B\" stroke-width=\"7\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/>\n<circle cx=\"90\" cy=\"170\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"200\" cy=\"170\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"330\" cy=\"170\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"128\" cy=\"236\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"332\" cy=\"104\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"140\" cy=\"74\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"360\" cy=\"141\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#6F7FA0\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"170\" r=\"11\" fill=\"#0A0F24\" stroke=\"#9FB0D8\" stroke-width=\"3.5\"/>\n<circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"170\" r=\"4.5\" fill=\"#9FB0D8\"/>\n</svg></div>\n<div class=\"absolute inset-0 rounded-2xl\" style=\"background:linear-gradient(78deg, transparent 55%, rgba(17,26,58,.92) 96%)\"></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flex flex-col items-center\" style=\"width:300px\">\n<div class=\"relative rounded-2xl border px-5 py-4 text-[19px] leading-snug\" style=\"background:rgba(56,189,248,.14); border-color:rgba(56,189,248,.5); color:#EEF2FF\">&#8220;Also color the stations by cuisine.&#8221;\n<div class=\"absolute -bottom-2 left-8 w-4 h-4 rotate-45 border-b border-r\" style=\"background:rgba(30,52,88,1); border-color:rgba(56,189,248,.5)\"></div>\n</div>\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 120 40\" class=\"mt-6\" style=\"width:120px\"><path d=\"M8 20 H98\" stroke=\"#38BDF8\" stroke-width=\"5\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/><path d=\"M86 8 L104 20 L86 32\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#38BDF8\" stroke-width=\"5\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\"/></svg>\n</div>\n<div class=\"relative rounded-2xl border p-5\" style=\"width:400px; height:340px; background:rgba(17,26,58,.75); border-color:rgba(56,189,248,.4); box-shadow:0 0 40px rgba(56,189,248,.12)\">\n<div class=\"flex items-center justify-between mb-1\">\n<div class=\"text-[15px] font-semibold\" style=\"color:#38BDF8\">v2</div>\n<div class=\"flex items-center gap-3 text-[14px]\" style=\"color:#9FB0D8\"><span class=\"flex items-center gap-1\">&#127843;<span class=\"inline-block w-2.5 h-2.5 rounded-full\" style=\"background:#34D399\"></span></span><span class=\"flex items-center gap-1\">&#127836;<span class=\"inline-block w-2.5 h-2.5 rounded-full\" style=\"background:#FBBF24\"></span></span><span class=\"flex items-center gap-1\">&#127837;<span class=\"inline-block w-2.5 h-2.5 rounded-full\" style=\"background:#F0ABFC\"></span></span></div>\n</div>\n<div style=\"height:270px\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 460 310\" class=\"w-full h-full\">\n<path d=\"M30 170 H430\" stroke=\"#38BDF8\" stroke-width=\"7\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/>\n<path d=\"M60 280 L400 60\" stroke=\"#818CF8\" stroke-width=\"7\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/>\n<path d=\"M60 80 L260 65 Q300 62 322 92 L390 180\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#FBBF24\" stroke-width=\"7\" stroke-linecap=\"round\"/>\n<circle cx=\"90\" cy=\"170\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#34D399\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"200\" cy=\"170\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FBBF24\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"330\" cy=\"170\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#F0ABFC\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"128\" cy=\"236\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#34D399\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"332\" cy=\"104\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#F0ABFC\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"140\" cy=\"74\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#FBBF24\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"360\" cy=\"141\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#34D399\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"170\" r=\"11\" fill=\"#0A0F24\" stroke=\"#EEF2FF\" stroke-width=\"3.5\"/>\n<circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"170\" r=\"4.5\" fill=\"#EEF2FF\"/>\n</svg></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"pb-10 text-center text-[19px]\" style=\"color:#9FB0D8\">Regrown, not repaired &#8212; no code review, just <span style=\"color:#38BDF8\">the sentence again.</span></div>\n</div>"
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "And no — this is not brand new. The spreadsheet got here first. A budget model in Excel is software for an audience of one. But the spreadsheet made you the programmer. You built it yourself, cell by cell, inside a grid. What's new is a double removal: the surface becomes arbitrary code, and the agent does the building. That double removal is the second pillar — the computer that builds — arriving for people who will never read code.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "comparison",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The honest precedent"
          },
          "title": "The spreadsheet got here first — at a price",
          "left": {
            "title": "Spreadsheet · no-code",
            "accentColor": "warning",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "bullets",
                "items": [
                  "You do the building",
                  "Inside a grid or block palette"
                ]
              }
            ],
            "footer": "Bespoke — but you became the programmer"
          },
          "right": {
            "title": "An agent that builds",
            "accentColor": "success",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "bullets",
                "items": [
                  "The agent does the building",
                  "Any surface — even a subway map"
                ]
              }
            ],
            "footer": "You don't assemble. You describe."
          },
          "callout": {
            "text": "The {highlight:double removal} is the actual novelty — both constraints gone at once.",
            "label": "What's new",
            "color": "highlight",
            "leftBar": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Now the honest part. This gives something up. Mass software is debugged by millions of people — every bug you never hit, someone else already found. Software for one has no such crowd. Its bugs ship to their only user. You. The spreadsheet taught this lesson too: the danger was never the visible screen. It was the invisible formula error nobody else ever checked.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "comparison",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The cost that relocates",
            "color": "danger"
          },
          "title": "Correctness doesn't vanish — it moves",
          "left": {
            "title": "Mass software",
            "accentColor": "info",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "value": "**Debugged by millions**, over years.",
                "bold": true
              }
            ],
            "footer": "You inherit everyone else's fixes"
          },
          "right": {
            "title": "Software for one",
            "accentColor": "danger",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "value": "The bug ships to **its only user: you.**",
                "bold": true
              }
            ],
            "footer": "No other eyes will ever run it"
          },
          "callout": {
            "text": "The wrong poster wall is harmless. The wrong {danger:portfolio chart} is not.",
            "label": "Old lesson",
            "color": "danger",
            "leftBar": true
          }
        }
      }
